AGI - The candidates for the presidency of the Islamic Republic "will not be many, the time to select them is little, but certainly the whole voting process will be managed so as to reduce the possibility that the reformists can enter the electoral race and have a chance". It is the prediction of Abdolrasool Divsallar>, an analyst of the Middle East Institute in Washington, according to which "the effect of the death of the President <a href="https://www.agi.it/video/2024-05-21/cosa-succede-iran-dopo-morte-raisi-26478616/">Ebrahim Raisi < politics/a> "The quick decision to indict the presidentials within 39 days (the Constitution gave up to a maximum of 50 days, ed.) indicates that the Islamic Republic is attentive to the consequences of a vacuum of power and aims to fill it immediately with another conservative candidate, avoiding an opening of the political system," explains Divsallar in an interview with the AGI.
&nbsp;
"It will prevail," according to the analyst, "a systemic logic, which does not think of many changes in the internal distribution of power: Conservatives will do anything to maintain their control quotas, because this is functional to the process of succession to the Supreme Guide", Ali Khamenei The rapidity with which the system reacted to the disappearance of Raisi, notes the Iranian analyst, "is interesting because it also reveals what would be the possible response to the death of Khamenei; the current situation is also a test on the preparation of the system to manage the processes of succession in emergencies and crisis".
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
Divsallar is not among the analysts who saw Raisi as a strong candidate for the after Khamenei: "I think his role was more to facilitate the process of choosing conservatives to get to the right candidate." The death of the president, one year before the natural expiry of his mandate, again lit the spotlight on the true node of the future of the Islamic Republic: the choice of the successor of the Supreme Guide». "I don't think that from the roster of the competitors to the presidentials of 28 June we will be able to understand a lot about the succession, but after the election, under the name of the next president we will certainly have a clearer idea of what political faction will have the greater opportunity to impose itself with a candidate" for the post-Khamenei, concludes the analyst: "Reformists, conservatives or moderates, representing different powers, and the blocking of security and military services that are not a unitary political actor but are distributed in the previous three groups." &nbsp;&nbsp;<br> &nbsp;
